---
import Layout from "../../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import ConcreteWallCalc from "../../../components/calculators/ConcreteWallCalc";
import { graphSchema, mathSolverSchema, howToSchema, faqPageSchema, breadcrumbListSchema } from "../../../lib/schema";
import RelatedCalculators from "../../../components/ui/RelatedCalculators.astro";

const canonical = "https://homeplanninghub.com/calculators/concrete/wall/";

const title = "Concrete Wall Calculator";
const description = "Calculate concrete volume for retaining walls, foundation walls, and basement walls. Automatically subtracts door and window openings.";

const PAGE_PATH = canonical.replace("https://homeplanninghub.com", "");
const schema = graphSchema(
  breadcrumbListSchema([
    { name: "Home", path: "/" },
    { name: "Concrete Calculators", path: "/calculators/concrete/" },
    { name: title, path: PAGE_PATH },
  ]),
  mathSolverSchema({
    name: "Concrete Wall Volume Calculator",
    description: "Calculates wall volume with door and window opening deductions for foundation and retaining walls.",
    formula: "V = (L × H - Openings) × T",
    url: canonical,
  }),
  howToSchema(
    "Calculate Concrete for a Wall",
    "Find the volume of concrete needed for a wall with opening deductions.",
    [
      {
        name: "Calculate gross face area",
        text: "Multiply the wall length by the wall height. All measurements in feet.",
      },
      {
        name: "Subtract openings",
        text: "Subtract the area of each door (≈21 sq ft for 3×7) and each window (≈12 sq ft for 3×4).",
      },
      {
        name: "Multiply by thickness",
        text: "Net area × wall thickness (in feet). Convert inches to feet by dividing by 12.",
      },
      {
        name: "Add waste factor",
        text: "Multiply by 1.05 to 1.10 (5-10% waste) and convert to cubic yards (÷27).",
      },
    ]
  ),
  faqPageSchema([
    {
      q: "How thick should a concrete retaining wall be?",
      a: "Under 4 feet tall: at least 8 inches at base, tapering to 6 inches at top. Over 4 feet: requires engineering, typically 12 inches or more at base with rebar.",
    },
    {
      q: "How do you calculate concrete for a wall with openings?",
      a: "Gross area = length × height. Subtract opening areas (door ≈21 sq ft, window ≈12 sq ft). Net area × wall thickness in feet = cubic feet.",
    },
    {
      q: "How much concrete for a 10×8 foundation wall?",
      a: "80 sq ft × 0.667 ft (8 inches) = 53.3 cu ft, or about 1.97 cu yd. Add 10% waste for ≈2.2 cu yd.",
    },
  ], canonical)
);
---

<Layout title={title} description={description} schema={schema}>
  <article class="max-w-4xl mx-auto flex flex-col gap-6">
    <header class="mb-2">
      <nav class="flex items-center gap-1.5 text-xs text-[var(--fg-muted)] mb-6" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
        <a href="/" class="hover:underline">home</a>
        <svg class="w-3 h-3" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path d="M9 18l6-6-6-6"/></svg>
        <a href="/calculators/concrete/" class="hover:underline">concrete</a>
        <svg class="w-3 h-3" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path d="M9 18l6-6-6-6"/></svg>
        <span class="text-[var(--fg-secondary)]">wall</span>
      </nav>
      <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-balance mb-3">Concrete Wall Calculator</h1>
      <p class="text-base text-[var(--fg-secondary)] leading-relaxed text-pretty">
        Calculate the concrete volume needed for foundation walls, retaining walls, and basement walls. This tool automatically subtracts standard door and window openings from the total volume, then applies your waste factor to produce precise cubic yard and bag count estimates.
      </p>
    </header>



    <section><ConcreteWallCalc client:visible /></section>

    <section>
      <h2 id="how-to-calculate" class="text-xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-4">How to Calculate Concrete Wall Volume</h2>
      <p class="text-sm text-[var(--fg-secondary)] leading-relaxed mb-4 text-pretty">
        Concrete walls are calculated by finding the gross face area, subtracting any openings, then multiplying by the wall thickness. Follow these steps:
      </p>
      <ol class="list-decimal pl-5 flex flex-col gap-3 text-sm text-[var(--fg-secondary)]">
        <li><strong>Calculate Gross Area:</strong> Multiply the wall length by the wall height.
          <div class="my-2 p-3 bg-[var(--bg-muted)] rounded-lg font-mono text-center text-xs">Gross Area = Length (ft) &times; Height (ft)</div>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Subtract Openings:</strong> Deduct standard doors (21 sq ft each) and windows (12 sq ft each) from the gross area.
          <div class="my-2 p-3 bg-[var(--bg-muted)] rounded-lg font-mono text-center text-xs">Net Area = Gross Area &minus; (Doors &times; 21) &minus; (Windows &times; 12)</div>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Calculate Volume:</strong> Convert thickness from inches to feet (divide by 12), then multiply by the net area.
          <div class="my-2 p-3 bg-[var(--bg-muted)] rounded-lg font-mono text-center text-xs">Volume (cu ft) = Net Area &times; [Thickness (in) &divide; 12]</div>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2 id="example-calculation" class="text-xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-4">Example Wall Calculation</h2>
      <p class="text-sm text-[var(--fg-secondary)] leading-relaxed mb-4 text-pretty">
        Let's calculate a <strong>20-foot long, 8-foot high basement wall</strong> that is <strong>8 inches thick</strong> with <strong>1 door and 2 windows</strong>:
      </p>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-5 flex flex-col gap-2 text-sm text-[var(--fg-secondary)]">
        <li><strong>Gross Area:</strong> 20 ft &times; 8 ft = 160 sq ft</li>
        <li><strong>Openings:</strong> 1 door (21 sq ft) + 2 windows (24 sq ft) = 45 sq ft</li>
        <li><strong>Net Area:</strong> 160 &minus; 45 = 115 sq ft</li>
        <li><strong>Thickness in Feet:</strong> 8 in &divide; 12 = 0.667 ft</li>
        <li><strong>Volume:</strong> 115 sq ft &times; 0.667 ft = 76.7 cu ft (~2.84 cubic yards)</li>
        <li><strong>Bags (80lb, with 10% waste):</strong> 84.4 cu ft &divide; 0.6 = <strong>141 bags</strong></li>
      </ul>
    </section>


    <section>
      <h2 id="common-mistakes" class="text-xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-4">Common Mistakes in Wall Pours</h2>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-5 flex flex-col gap-3 text-sm text-[var(--fg-secondary)] text-pretty">
        <li><strong>Forgetting Opening Deductions:</strong> Doors and windows can account for 10-30% of a wall's face area. Failing to subtract them leads to significant over-ordering and wasted concrete costs.</li>
        <li><strong>Underestimating Form Pressure:</strong> Tall walls (over 4 feet) generate enormous hydrostatic pressure on formwork. Use strong forms with tight tie spacing, or pour in lifts of 4 feet with a short set time between lifts.</li>
        <li><strong>Not Accounting for Footing Key:</strong> Many foundation walls include a keyway groove in the footing that adds 2-5% to the wall volume. Include this in your estimate to avoid running short.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2 id="faq" class="text-xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <details class="rounded-xl border border-[var(--border)] bg-[var(--card-bg)] p-4">
          <summary class="text-sm font-semibold cursor-pointer"><h3 class="text-sm font-semibold m-0">How thick should a concrete retaining wall be?</h3></summary>
          <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-[var(--fg-secondary)] leading-relaxed text-pretty">A concrete retaining wall under 4 feet tall should be at least 8 inches thick at the base, tapering to 6 inches at the top. Walls over 4 feet require engineering design and typically need 12 inches or more at the base with rebar reinforcement.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="rounded-xl border border-[var(--border)] bg-[var(--card-bg)] p-4">
          <summary class="text-sm font-semibold cursor-pointer"><h3 class="text-sm font-semibold m-0">How do you calculate concrete volume for a wall with openings?</h3></summary>
          <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-[var(--fg-secondary)] leading-relaxed text-pretty">Multiply the wall length by the height to get the gross area. Subtract the area of each door (approximately 21 sq ft for a standard 3x7 door) and each window (approximately 12 sq ft for a standard 3x4 window). Multiply the net area by the wall thickness in feet to get cubic feet.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="rounded-xl border border-[var(--border)] bg-[var(--card-bg)] p-4">
          <summary class="text-sm font-semibold cursor-pointer"><h3 class="text-sm font-semibold m-0">How much concrete do I need for a 10x8 foundation wall?</h3></summary>
          <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-[var(--fg-secondary)] leading-relaxed text-pretty">A 10-foot long, 8-foot high wall with 8-inch thickness has a gross area of 80 square feet. With no openings, the volume is 80 sq ft x 0.667 ft = 53.3 cubic feet, or approximately 1.97 cubic yards. Add 10% waste for a total of about 2.2 cubic yards.</p>
        </details>
      </div>
    </section>

    <RelatedCalculators slug="concrete-wall" />
  </article>
</Layout>
